=== TASK ===
# Privacy Policy Page

## Overview
Build a legal Privacy Policy page for Archject that clearly explains how user and client data are collected, used, stored, and protected; describes user rights (access, export, deletion); and documents backup & recovery and data portability features. The page should be a public, SEO-friendly, accessible web page integrated with the product UI (project workspaces and account settings), link to backup/export features, and provide an authenticated flow for account data export and deletion requests. Also ensure the page design and copy adhere to Archject’s design system and voice.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
This Privacy Policy Page is a public-facing legal page hosted on the marketing site and linked from the app footer, account settings, and client-facing portals. Its goals are to:
- Communicate Archject’s privacy practices succinctly and legally (data collected, purpose, lawfulness, storage and retention).
- Explain data subject rights (access, rectification, portability, deletion, restriction, objection) and how to exercise them.
- Describe Backup & Recovery practices: backup cadence, retention, encryption, restore procedures, and availability guarantees.
- Describe Data Portability: how customers can request/export account archives and receive Decision Log exports in machine- and human-readable formats.
- Provide contact details and a privacy request form/email/portal; outline response SLA for privacy requests.
- Provide links to related pages: Terms of Service, Data Processing Agreement (if applicable), Security Page, and Support/Contact.

Connected features and integrations:
- Backup & Recovery: explained in policy text and linked to the app’s “Account Export” and “Restore” functionality.
- Account Export & Data Deletion UI: authenticated API endpoints to generate and deliver export archives (.zip with JSON/CSV and PDFs) and to queue deletions with audit trail.
- Landing Page: link to privacy policy from marketing/landing site footer and trust/security section.
- No external APIs are required for the policy text itself, but backend APIs for exports and deletion will be used.

UI elements & visual guidance:
- Page header: H1 “Privacy Policy” with short summary blurb beneath.
- Section list/TOC (sticky on wide screens) for quick navigation to main sections: What We Collect, How We Use Data, Storage & Security, Backups & Recovery, Data Retention, Your Rights, How to Export/Delete Data, Third-Party Processors, Contact & Complaints, Changes to Policy.
- Content cards: Each major section should be presented in a white card with subtle shadow and clear headings (H2). Use muted gray for explanatory text and accent (#0052CC) for links and CTA buttons (Export Data, Submit Request).
- CTA area: Prominent “Request Account Export” and “Request Data Deletion” buttons that either open the user settings modal (if authenticated) or show instructions to sign in / contact privacy@archject.com.
- Privacy request form (modal or page): authenticated form for users to request export/deletion, with fields for verification and confirmation. For public visitors, provide contact email and link to Support/Help Center.
- Accessibility: semantic HTML headings, skip links, high contrast text, keyboard-focusable elements, aria-live regions for request feedback.
- SEO: meta title, description, structured data (FAQ or ContactPoint where applicable).
- Visual style: adhere exactly to provided color palette, typography, spacing, and card/nav guidelines.

API integrations:
- Backend endpoints to create/export account archives, queue deletion requests, and query backup status. Internal notification/email for privacy team on requests.
- No external third-party API is mandated; if third-party processors are used (e.g., CDNs, storage, analytics), they should be listed in the policy text and referenced in the DB for compliance.

## Components to Build
- Public Privacy Policy page (marketing route) with full legal content and TOC.
- Sticky Table of Contents component for wide viewports.
- Policy content cards (reusable Card component following design system).
- Authenticated Account Export UI: a modal/page in account settings that triggers an export job, shows progress/status, and provides downloadable archive.
- Authenticated Data Deletion Request UI: a modal/page to request account deletion or data minimization, with verification steps (password/re-authentication and confirmation checkbox).
- Privacy Request API endpoints: create export job, fetch job status, download archive, create deletion request, fetch deletion request status.
- Background job processor: generates export archives, uploads to secure storage, notifies user when ready, and stores audit logs.
- Backup & Recovery summary block in policy: static explanatory content with link to “Backup & Recovery” page/section in Security docs.
- Email templates and notification flows for request initiation, completion, and errors.
- Admin dashboard endpoints/webhooks for privacy team to view and process requests (optional minimal list view).

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
Pages & components:
- /privacy (public route):
  - Header: H1 “Privacy Policy”, subhead summary (1–2 sentences).
  - TOC (left sticky on desktop, collapsible on mobile) linking to internal anchors.
  - Content area: series of Card components for each section:
    - What We Collect
    - How We Use Your Data
    - Legal Bases & Processors
    - Storage, Security & Encryption
    - Backups & Recovery (details: frequency, retention, encryption, restore SLA)
    - Data Retention & Deletion
    - Data Portability & Account Export
    - Cookies & Tracking
    - Children’s Data
    - International Transfers
    - How to Contact Us / Make a Request
    - Changes to Policy
  - Footer links: Terms, Security, Support, Contact, Cookie Settings, landing page link.
  - Buttons: “Request Account Export” and “Request Data Deletion” present and behave differently based on auth state:
    - If unauthenticated: clicking opens Sign In modal or shows instructions & contact email.
    - If authenticated: opens respective modal or navigates to Account > Data tab.

- Account Settings > Data (authenticated route):
  - Section card: “Export your data”
    - Button: “Request Export” (primary style #0052CC)
    - Info text: expected time (e.g., up to 24 hours), formats (JSON, CSV, PDF Decision Logs), what’s included.
    - Last export history list with status badges (Published/Processing/Error) and download links for completed ones.
  - Section card: “Delete your account”
    - Danger-styled CTA (outline or ghost with red text) to start deletion workflow.
    - Display consequences checklist and retention/restore window.
    - Re-authentication input (password or 2FA prompt) and final confirmation checkbox.
  - Section card: “Backup & Recovery” (read-only summary) linking to Security docs; show backup cadence and snapshot retention.

- Privacy Request Modal/Forms:
  - Fields: user id (auto), email (auto), request type (Export/Delete/Other), verification method (password), optional notes.
  - Submit button disabled until re-authenticated/confirmed.
  - After submit: show job id, estimated completion time, and link to request status.

- Notifications & toasts for job progress and completion with link to download.

Accessibility & behavior:
- Use semantic headings, aria-labels, role attributes.
- Keyboard navigable TOC and modals.
- Provide clear error messages and inline validation.
- Responsive: single-column on mobile; sticky TOC hidden on narrow screens.

Styling:
- Follow Typography & Layout specs.
- Cards, buttons, badges, and forms per Key Design Elements and Color Palette.

### Backend
APIs, jobs, and storage:
- Database tables:
  - users (if not already present) — user account data.
  - data_exports:
    - id (uuid)
    - user_id (fk)
    - status (enum: requested, processing, completed, failed)
    - format (json,csv,pdf,zip — support multiple)
    - storage_key (s3 path)
    - size_bytes
    - requested_at, started_at, completed_at, expires_at
    - error_message
  - deletion_requests:
    - id (uuid)
    - user_id (fk)
    - status (pending, scheduled, completed, cancelled, failed)
    - verification_method (password, 2fa)
    - scheduled_for (timestamp for irreversible deletion if hold window)
    - requested_at, completed_at, error_message
  - backups (optional summary table):
    - id, job_timestamp, snapshot_key, size_bytes, retention_until, status
  - audit_logs:
    - id, actor_id, action_type, target_type, target_id, metadata JSON, timestamp

- Storage:
  - Secure object storage (S3 or S3-compatible). All archives encrypted at rest; pre-signed time-limited download URLs.

- Endpoints:
  - POST /api/v1/privacy/exports
    - Auth required. Body: { formats: [json,csv,pdf], include: [decisions,projects,comments,attachments] }
    - Creates data_exports record, enqueues job, returns { export_id }.
  - GET /api/v1/privacy/exports/:id
    - Auth required. Returns export status and presigned_url if completed.
  - GET /api/v1/privacy/exports
    - Auth required. List recent exports for user.
  - POST /api/v1/privacy/deletions
    - Auth required. Body: { retention_window_days? (optional) } — creates deletion_request, triggers verification, schedules deletion.
  - GET /api/v1/privacy/deletions/:id
    - Auth required. Returns status and expected deletion date.
  - GET /api/v1/privacy/backups (admin-only)
    - Returns backup cadence and snapshot metadata (for admin dashboard).
  - Webhook/email notifications invoked by job completion/failure.

- Background job logic:
  - Worker processes export jobs: gather all user/project data (Decision Logs, attachments), stream into structured formats:
    - JSON: nested objects representing workspace, projects, decisions, comments, approvals, timestamps, user ids.
    - CSV: flat lists for decision records and user lists.
    - PDFs: render Decision Log human-readable report (styled per brand).
    - Attachments: included in zip under /attachments/.
  - Archive creation: incremental memory usage, stream to storage, compute size, store metadata in data_exports.
  - Security: redact or include PII per user opt-in; log all steps to audit_logs.

- Admin tools:
  - Admin endpoints to see pending deletion/export jobs, cancel, retry, and manual restore from backup (restricted to admin roles).

### Integration
- Frontend calls respective endpoints with auth tokens (JWT or session cookie). Use secure fetch with CSRF where applicable.
- Background worker (e.g., Sidekiq, Bull, Celery) handles long-running export and deletion processing, writes to storage, and updates DB.
- Notification service (email + in-app notifications) to alert user on completion using templates.
- Storage links returned should expire (e.g., 24–72 hours).
- Deletion requests should set a hold window (e.g., 14 days) during which user can cancel; after the window, permanent deletion runs and relevant backups are marked for purging per retention policy (log purge events in audit_logs).
- Backup policy described in policy page must reflect the actual implementation: frequency (e.g., nightly snapshots), retention (e.g., 90 days), encryption, and geographic replication.

## User Experience Flow
1. Visitor lands on /privacy: reads overview, navigates via TOC to desired section.
2. Authenticated user sees “Request Account Export” and “Request Data Deletion” CTAs.
3. User clicks “Request Account Export”:
   - If unauthenticated: prompt to sign in or contact privacy@archject.com.
   - If authenticated: open export modal where user picks formats and submit.
   - Frontend calls POST /api/v1/privacy/exports; returns export_id and status “requested”. Display optimistic UI with estimated time.
   - Worker processes job, creates archive, stores in S3, updates data_exports to completed.
   - User receives email and in-app notification with download link; user can also view export history in Account Settings.
4. User clicks “Request Data Deletion”:
   - Modal shows consequences and requires re-authentication (password/2FA) and explicit confirmation.
   - POST /api/v1/privacy/deletions creates deletion_request and sets scheduled_for with hold window (e.g., 14 days).
   - User is informed of cancel window and receives email/in-app notification.
   - Admin/automation purges account data after window; audit_log created. Backups overlapping request are retained until backup retention policy expires; policy page explains this.
5. Support / privacy team receives notifications for any manual processing required and can view request metadata in admin dashboard.

